status_message: In this photograph taken on December 27, 2015, Indian farmer Waghjibhai Jenabhai Chavdanear sits on a traditional bed near recently installed solar panels, which power water pumps to irrigate fields in the village of Dhundi, some 90kms from Ahmedabad. With the help of a subsidy of 95 percent of the cost from The International Water Management Institute and The Tata Trust, six farmers in the village of the western state of Gujarat have each installed six solar panels at a cost to them of 55,000 Indian Rupees (USD831) - the remaining 5 percent - and will sell on surplus electricity created to the state electricity provider. Thus enabling savings in the cost of diesel which is typically used to power irrigation devices. AFP PHOTO / Sam PANTHAKY

Early this year, senior Congress leader Janardan Dwivedi, the party's upper caste face had created a stir calling  for an end to reservation on caste lines, forcing the party to distance itself  both in the Parliament and outside, lest it invoked political repercussions.  Now another senior leader  and former law minister H R Bhardwaj, has culled a letter from India's first prime minister Jawaharlal Nehru opposing quota systems on caste and communal lines. In a book titled "Nehru-Gazing at Tomorrow", scheduled to be released here on Wednesday by Vice-President Hamid Ansari, Bhradwaj, another  Brahmin face in the party writes that Nehru's idea of social justice was to create educational opportunities and reservations at some preliminary stages, not at later stages.  "Because he (Nehru) believed that his ambition to build India with first-rate citizens (meritorious) should not be constrained by too much reservation at all levels," writes Bhardwaj, who till recently was Governor of Karnataka.

http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-hr-bhardwaj-stirs-hornet-s-nest-quotes-jawaharlal-nehru-demanding-end-to-caste-based-reservation-2022355

World's largest active volcano shows signs of life in Hawaii

Mauna Loa, the world's largest active volcano, has rumbled back to life in Hawaii over the past 13 months with more seismic activity than at any time since its last eruption, scientists say, while calling it too soon to predict another blast.

The volcano, which last erupted in 1975 and 1984, has been rattled since March 2013 by earthquakes of the same type and in the same location as the temblors that preceded those explosions, said Wes Thelen, a seismologist for the US Geological Survey's Hawaiian Volcano Observatory.

status_message:
In dangerous territory: The growing incidence of rapes is due to regressive mindset and lack of safe social spaces

Until a few weeks ago, most of us had a barely passing familiarity with Badaun in Uttar Pradesh. Around 200 kms and less than a four-hour drive from the national capital, Delhi, the area hit the headlines after the brutal rape and murder of two teenaged girls. It is an old story, told again with callous violence and viciousness. Two cousins — some accounts put them at 12 and 15 years of age, others at 14 and 15 — had to attend to nature's call. They had no toilet in their house and they went to the fields to relieve themselves. They never returned home. Their bodies were found hanging — their dupattas tied around their necks — from a mango tree. They had been raped, strangled and strung up like the spoils from a shikaar. Two young men from a neighbouring village, and two police officers are believed to be the culprits.

status_message:
Here's the story of Mumbaikar Anita Lobo. 

A traffic warden who has been voluntarily regulating traffic in Bandra-Khar for the last ten years. 

In a shocking development, she was served a notice terminating her services for pulling up industries minister Narayan Rane's son Nilesh Rane for blocking traffic in January.

Today, there's some good news: 

Jt CP says her dismissal order has been revoked: 
http://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/1820143/report-bandra-khar-traffic-warden-anita-lobo-s-dismissal-order-revoked-jt-cp-traffic-vivek-phansalkar

This comes after Bandra activists protested. 
But what if they hadn't? 
How was the termination notice passed in the first place?
For how long will ordinary citizens and cops be bullied by politicians in power?

status_message:
Are you attending DNA Wheelocity this weekend?

https://www.facebook.com/events/434974323255204/

For those who are, get ready to meet Nirvana. She's a beauty!
Designer Adil Dumasia tells her more about her:

The owner of this bike told me one thing before customizing 'I do not want anything negative on the bike, eg. Skulls, devil figure, etc. Would prefer some gentle figure with +ve vibes.

I immediately thought of the "Buddha" face as I associate a lot of +ve vibes and I'm very much inclined to the gentle expression on the Buddha face. I searched the internet for a Buddha face with open eyes as I had imagined a Buddha on the tank which would be looking at the rider as he rides the bike. I couldn't find any such image hence I came up with my own imagination of the Buddha with open eyes and I sketched it down. 

I took 3.5 months to build this bike as it had to be very unique. I designed and fabricated the rolling chassis. There is a lot of detailing on this bike like, all edges are sharp not rounded, there is a Buddhist chant on the fork shields, the handle bar weights have inbuilt forward/rear indicators, the tank is sharp and sleek, the swing arm and the under-seat has inbuilt tail lamps, its belt driven, rear wheel has been fabricated, the triple exhaust is hand made by, etc.

There is a lot of soul that has gone into making this bike. She attracts loads of attention on the road and mobs collect wherever I stop. She sure is a head-turner. I have to answer questions tossed at me while I wait for traffic lights, people roll down their car windows, give complements and click snaps on their cell phones. She is not looking a good looking bike but has loads of power and has a stunningly steady ride. I have done a top speed of 135 kmph on this bike and I recently rode her all the way to Goa and back for the Royal Enfield Rider Mania Event and even won the 1st prize for the Best Custom Bike contest.

My aim is to prove that I would continue to make not only good looking bikes but great riding bikes too.

status_message:
Chocolate can give you the same high as opium.

According to research by the University of Michigan, chocolate has an effect on the brain similar to that of opium. In the study, a neurotransmitter called enkephalin — an endorphin with similar properties to opium — surged when rats were fed M&M chocolates.

And when a drug was used to stimulate the area of the brain that releases enkephalin, the rats devoured twice as many M&Ms, presumably connecting the taste to this surge of endorphins.

(Read complete report http://dnai.in/bi7z)

Will you cut down your intake of chocolates now?

'Khadoba-Mhalasa Vivaah' festival organised at Pal, a small village around 140 km from Pune, saw devotion and fervour flow to its fullest to commemorate the marriage ceremony of two Gods — Khandoba and Mhalasa.

The village seemed to wear a golden attire on the pious date, thanks to the huge amount of bhandara (yellow dust) offered to the gods by the devotees along with the chants of 'Yelkot Yelkot Jai Malhar' and 'Khandobacha Navana Changbhala'. 

More than 9,00,000 people attended the fest on the auspicious occasion. -Aniruddha Rajandekar, DNA

status_message:
The Mumbai protesters of the Delhi gangrape at Azad Maidaan had a few demands:

1. Special parliament session within a week to consider death sentence for henious crimes against women/minors.
2. Fast track courts meant for rape cases should announce the punishment within one month.
3. Total crime cases against women reported 2,28,650 and the conviction percentage is 27%. We need stronger law to tackle any crime against women.
4. Police reforms needed (The budget on security needs to be improved) and a separate section of police will protect VIPs and the rest will be in service of common man.

Photo: Mahafreed Irani, DNA
